       <div id="comment-127">
        <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
         <strong>
          Mell
         </strong>
         <span>
          October 4, 2015 at 11:30 am
         </span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
         <p>
          Ps I didn’t realize you didn’t go the PT route… Sound like it’s going well without… I’ve read that for others too. But as you said … Movement and exercises are essential!
          <br />
          For me, and for folks considering whether or not to go: my injury was kind of a freak thing during everyday activity so I have a lot of fear of regular life activity. PT is actually helping me with my confidence.
          <br />
          PT helps strengthen the stabilizers in the ankle..
          <br />
          But they also help you learn to mimic awkward balance and walking situations in a controlled and safe environment. If your ankle is locked up tight they manually help to loosen it up… And the education around the anatomy of the injury, tissue and healing is great.
         </p>
        </div>
        <div class="reply">
        </div>
       </div>
      </li>
      <!-- #comment-## -->
      <li id="li-comment-128" class="comment byuser comment-author-laura bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1 clearfix">
       <img width="38" height="38" class="avatar avatar-38 photo" srcset="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6d7cb8d85934e21a318dcf6525130c6b?s=76&d=mm&r=g 2x" src="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6d7cb8d85934e21a318dcf6525130c6b?s=38&d=mm&r=g" alt="" />
       <div id="comment-128">
        <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
         <strong>
          Laura
         </strong>
         <span>
          October 4, 2015 at 11:49 am
         </span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
         <p>
          Thank you for your posts!
          <img style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" class="wp-smiley" alt=":)" src="http://myorifankle.com/wp-includes/images/smilies/simple-smile.png" />
          You know, I didn’t INTEND to drop out of PT, lol. I do believe it’s important, and I know it sounds lame to say I was too busy. But this honestly happened at a time when I had so many irons in the fire I just couldn’t bring myself to go there when I was already stressing my ankle to its limits and probably beyond. I have been doing some of the exercises they showed me at home, but I will admit it’s often hit and miss. However, I do A LOT of ankle circles and flexion and extension as I watch TV or whatever to increase my range of motion. So even though it hasn’t been against resistance, I’m sure that’s been helping quite a bit.
         </p>
         <p>
          Now, because I feel like my progress has stalled somewhat, I’m wondering if I should go back to PT since my life has now calmed down and I have more time. I suppose it’s not too late. Of course, the other consideration is whether my insurance will help me out with the cost, but I can look into that.
         </p>
         <p>
          It’s funny you mentioned how it was a freak accident for you because it was for me too. That is hard to deal with, isn’t it, because we can’t just say, “Well, learned my lesson, I’m never going skydiving again!” LOL. I can’t stop using stairs just because I stepped off the last one in just the wrong way that it broke bones! So I’m fearful too that it could happen again.
         </p>
        </div>
        <div class="reply">
        </div>
       </div>
      </li>
      <!-- #comment-## -->
      <li id="li-comment-129" class="comment byuser comment-author-laura bypostauthor odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 clearfix">
       <img width="38" height="38" class="avatar avatar-38 photo" srcset="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6d7cb8d85934e21a318dcf6525130c6b?s=76&d=mm&r=g 2x" src="http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/6d7cb8d85934e21a318dcf6525130c6b?s=38&d=mm&r=g" alt="" />
       <div id="comment-129">
        <div class="comment-meta commentmetadata">
         <strong>
          Laura
         </strong>
         <span>
          October 4, 2015 at 11:54 am
         </span>
        </div>
        <div class="text">
         <p>
          It’s hard not knowing whether the pain we are feeling is normal, just the result of using those muscles again to hold ourselves up, or is a sign of something wrong. I’ve been considering calling my surgeon for another x-ray and checkup because sometimes my foot hurts so bad I’m SURE there’s got to be something wrong. But then it goes away for a while.
         </p>
         <p>
          To answer your questions, my balance is pretty good. Or at least as good as it was before, and clearly I was a klutz, so that’s not saying much! LOL. I don’t use crutches, a brace, or anything anymore, not on the trip either because I already had so much to lug around. I’m afraid to sell the crutches, though; I guess my crutches are a crutch, haha.
         </p>
         <p>
          I can’t jog but I can walk briskly, yes, once my ankle limbers up. Each time I get up from the computer or the couch or get out of the car, I’m starting from square one, it feels like, as far as stiffness goes. But after a couple of minutes, I can walk as though nothing ever happened. If I do it too long, I’ll pay for it later, but for short distances, I do quite well. How about you? You’re a couple months behind me but you’re probably at that point where you’re starting to function normally again…?
         </p>
        </div>
        <div class="reply">
        </div>
       </div>
      </li>
      <!-- #comment-## -->
      <li id="li-comment-132" class="comment even thread-even depth-1 clearfix">
